{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17505585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17505585"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:32:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2457"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2457"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.47,0.39,0.04,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81577"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2457","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2457"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2457"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66932"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3758"},{"type":"tags","id":"8151"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2037"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81577"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of fatigue and feeling cold. She has no localising symptoms of infection and no known sick contacts. She has metastatic breast cancer and is receiving regular chemotherapy, with her last dose one week ago. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications apart from her cancer treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 115/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. The remainder of the examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transfer to hospital for immediate assessment","Commence oral amoxicillin-clavulanate","Observe in clinic with regular vital sign checks","Arrange urgent outpatient blood tests","Discharge with advice to return if symptoms worsen"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suspicious of febrile neutropenia - fever in the setting of recent chemotherapy. It can be diagnosed with a single fever \u0026gt;38.3\u00b0C or a temperature \u0026gt;38\u00b0C for at least one hour with a neurotrophic count \u0026lt;500 cells/microlitre. A full blood count is not available in this case to diagnose the latter; however, this presentation is a medical emergency requiring immediate intervention, even before confirming the neutrophil count.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDue to the lack of available circulating neutrophils, patients with febrile neutropenia are unable to mount an appropriate inflammatory response to an infective agent, and therefore can present with non-specific signs. This patient\u0027s tachycardia and hypotension are also supportive of a possible inflammatory or infective process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to hospital for immediate assessment\u003C/strong\u003E is essential as these patients require urgent broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics, ideally within one hour of presentation. The patient\u0027s tachycardia suggests early sepsis, further emphasising the urgency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECommence oral amoxicillin-clavulanate\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate as febrile neutropenia requires broad-spectrum intravenous antibiotics (typically piperacillin-tazobactam or similar) which cannot be administered in primary care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObserve in clinic with regular vital sign checks\u003C/strong\u003E would delay definitive care. While monitoring is important, the priority is rapid transfer to a facility where appropriate antibiotics can be administered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange urgent outpatient blood tests\u003C/strong\u003E would delay critical treatment. While confirming neutropenia with a FBC and performing sepsis investigations in the form of blood cultures is important, treatment should not be delayed waiting for results in a patient with high clinical suspicion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarge with advice to return if symptoms worsen\u003C/strong\u003E would be dangerous. Neutropenic patients can deteriorate rapidly and may present with minimal symptoms due to their impaired inflammatory response.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing suspected febrile neutropenia is early recognition and immediate referral for appropriate antibiotic therapy. Blood cultures should be taken before antibiotics where possible, but should not delay antibiotic administration if there would be a significant time delay.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Febrile neutropenia should be suspected in any patient on chemotherapy presenting with fever (\u003E38.3\u00b0C) or sustained temperature \u003E38\u00b0C for 1 hour.","Urgent hospital transfer for immediate broad-spectrum IV antibiotics is essential, ideally within 1 hour of presentation.","Patients may present with minimal symptoms or signs due to their impaired inflammatory response."],"references":["Rolston, K \u0026 Nesher, L. Febrile Neutropenia (Online). BMJ. Feb 2021. Access at: https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-us/950.","Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd. Febrile Neutropenia (Internet). 2019. Access at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.proxy.library.adelaide.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=febrile-neutropenia\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic\u0026topicNavigation=navigateTopic#toc_d1e155."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66932"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2457"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66932"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T14:30:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T14:30:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2457"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81577"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"m